################################################################################
# Notes:
#
# 1. Local State (Default):
#    - State stored in terraform.tfstate (local machine)
#    - Suitable for development only
#    - NOT suitable for production or team collaboration
#
# 2. Remote State Benefits:
#    - Centralized state management
#    - Team collaboration
#    - Backup and recovery
#    - State locking (prevents concurrent modifications)
#    - Audit trail
#
# 3. Setting Up S3 Backend (AWS):
#    ```bash
#    # Create S3 bucket
#    aws s3api create-bucket --bucket devops-academy-terraform-state --region us-east-1
#    
#    # Enable versioning
#    aws s3api put-bucket-versioning --bucket devops-academy-terraform-state \
#      --versioning-configuration Status=Enabled
#    
#    # Create DynamoDB table for state locking
#    aws dynamodb create-table --table-name terraform-locks \
#      --attribute-definitions AttributeName=LockID,AttributeType=S \
#      --key-schema AttributeName=LockID,KeyType=HASH \
#      --provisioned-throughput ReadCapacityUnits=5,WriteCapacityUnits=5
#    ```
#
# 4. Migrating to Remote State:
#    ```bash
#    # Uncomment backend block in backend.tf
#    terraform init
#    # Terraform will ask: "Do you want to copy existing state to the new backend?"
#    # Type: yes
#    ```
#
# 5. Viewing Remote State:
#    ```bash
#    terraform state list          # List all resources
#    terraform state show resource # Show specific resource
#    terraform state pull         # Download state locally
#    ```
################################################################################
